---
import Layout from "../Layout.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import HeaderHero from "../components/HeaderHero.astro";
import WaitListForm from "../components/WaitListForm.astro";
import Card from "../components/elements/Card.astro";
import Grid from "../components/elements/Grid.astro";
import Heading from "../components/elements/Heading.astro";
import Paragraph from "../components/elements/Paragraph.astro";
import SVG from "../components/elements/SVG.astro";
import Section from "../components/elements/Section.astro";

const {
  headerColor1 = "rgba(150, 140, 150, 0.1)",
  headerColor2 = "rgba(150, 40, 50, 0.0)",
  headerColor3 = "rgba(150, 150, 150, 0.1)",
  linearColor1 = "rgba(150, 40, 50, 0.1)",
  background = "linear-gradient(135deg, #f0f7e522, #f0f0f522);",
} = Astro.props || {};
---

<Layout
  title="About — Mermind"
  description="Learn about Mermind's mission to build a neutral operational intelligence layer for e-commerce. Built by operators, for operators."
  canonicalUrl={`${Astro.site}about`}
>
  <Header
    color1={headerColor1}
    color2={headerColor2}
    color3={headerColor3}
    linearColor1={linearColor1}
    background={background}
  >
    <HeaderHero
      paddingY="lg"
      altTitle="Who We Are"
      title="We saw a gap that should not exist"
      lead="Mermind is built by people who have worked inside real e-commerce operations — and kept running into the same problem. Not a lack of data. A lack of understanding."
      variant="default"
      size="default"
    >
      <div slot="graphic">
        <SVG size="100%">
          <path d="M16 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"></path>
          <path d="M16 3.128a4 4 0 0 1 0 7.744"></path>
          <path d="M22 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-3-3.87"></path>
          <circle cx="9" cy="7" r="4"></circle>
        </SVG>
      </div>
    </HeaderHero>
  </Header>
  <main>
    <Section>
      <div slot="header" class="section--header">
        <div class="alt-title">Where It Started</div>
        <Heading level={2} size="xl">
          Built from the inside out by operators
        </Heading>
        <Paragraph size="lg" dimmed>
          By operators. For operators. We needed a system that understands.
        </Paragraph>
      </div>
      <Grid columns={1} gap="2rem">
        <Card>
          <div>
            <Paragraph>
              Mermind did not start with a market map or a whiteboard full of
              opportunity sizing.
            </Paragraph>

            <p>
              It started with a specific, recurring frustration — the kind that
              builds quietly over years of running real e-commerce operations.
            </p>

            <p>
              Products disappearing from listings without explanation. Tracking
              breaking silently for days before anyone noticed. Margins eroding
              in ways that no single report could fully account for.
              Integrations failing in the gaps between tools, where no one was
              watching.
            </p>

            <p>
              Every time, the discovery came too late. Every time, the cost was
              already paid.
            </p>

            <p>
              The instinct was to find a tool that could help. Something that
              sat across the whole operation, understood what was happening, and
              surfaced problems before they compounded. Something that did not
              require a data team to operate, or a dashboard review to trigger.
            </p>

            <p>That tool did not exist.</p>

            <p>
              What existed were analytics platforms that reported on the past,
              monitoring tools that fired alerts when someone had already
              thought to define a threshold, and apps that each optimized their
              own narrow slice of the operation — none of them talking to each
              other, none of them seeing the full picture.
            </p>

            <p>
              The gap was not in the data. There was plenty of data. The gap was
              in understanding — a system that could look across everything
              running an e-commerce operation and tell you, clearly and early,
              what was going wrong and why.
            </p>

            <p>
              Mermind is the answer to that gap. Not built by people who
              observed the problem from the outside — but by people who lived
              inside it, made the costly mistakes that come from not seeing
              things clearly enough, and decided to build the system that should
              have existed all along.
            </p>

            <p>By operators. For operators.</p>
          </div>
        </Card>
        <Card>
          <Heading level={3} size="md">Mission</Heading>
          <Paragraph margin="sm">
            To build a neutral operational intelligence layer that helps
            e-commerce teams understand what is happening in their operations,
            prevent what should not happen, and act with clarity at every stage
            of growth.
          </Paragraph>
        </Card>
      </Grid>
    </Section>
    <Section>
      <div slot="header" class="section--header">
        <div class="alt-title">How We Build</div>
        <Heading level={2} size="2xl">Our Values</Heading>
        <Paragraph size="lg">
          We build Mermind the way we would want an intelligence layer built for
          our own operations.
        </Paragraph>
      </div>
      <Grid columns={2} gap="2rem">
        <Card>
          <div class="icon">
            <SVG size="48" dimmed>
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="6"></circle>
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="2"></circle>
            </SVG>
          </div>
          <Heading level={3}>Accuracy Over Breadth</Heading>
          <Paragraph>
            We would rather do one thing correctly than many things
            approximately. A system that is sometimes wrong about important
            things is not a better tool — it is noise that costs you decisions.
            We start narrow and expand only when the foundation is proven.
          </Paragraph>
        </Card>
        <Card>
          <div class="icon">
            <SVG size="48" dimmed>
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
              <path d="M9.09 9a3 3 0 0 1 5.83 1c0 2-3 3-3 3"></path>
              <path d="M12 17h.01"></path>
            </SVG>
          </div>
          <Heading level={3}>Explanation Before Action</Heading>
          <Paragraph>
            Mermind will not surface a recommendation it cannot explain. Every
            insight has a traceable reason. Every alert has a clear cause. This
            is not a feature — it is the architectural principle that makes the
            intelligence trustworthy.
          </Paragraph>
        </Card>
        <Card>
          <div class="icon">
            <SVG size="48" dimmed>
              <path
                d="M19.414 14.414C21 12.828 22 11.5 22 9.5a5.5 5.5 0 0 0-9.591-3.676.6.6 0 0 1-.818.001A5.5 5.5 0 0 0 2 9.5c0 2.3 1.5 4 3 5.5l5.535 5.362a2 2 0 0 0 2.879.052 2.12 2.12 0 0 0-.004-3 2.124 2.124 0 1 0 3-3 2.124 2.124 0 0 0 3.004 0 2 2 0 0 0 0-2.828l-1.881-1.882a2.41 2.41 0 0 0-3.409 0l-1.71 1.71a2 2 0 0 1-2.828 0 2 2 0 0 1 0-2.828l2.823-2.762"
              ></path>
            </SVG>
          </div>
          <Heading level={3}>Earn Trust, Don't Assume It</Heading>
          <Paragraph>
            Trust in a system is built through demonstrated accuracy over time,
            not through a promise at onboarding. Mermind starts with a narrow
            scope, proves its judgment on real operational problems, and earns a
            broader role only as that trust compounds.
          </Paragraph>
        </Card>
        <Card>
          <div class="icon">
            <SVG size="48" dimmed>
              <path d="M12 6v16"></path>
              <path d="m19 13 2-1a9 9 0 0 1-18 0l2 1"></path>
              <path d="M9 11h6"></path>
              <circle cx="12" cy="4" r="2"></circle>
            </SVG>
          </div>
          <Heading level={3}>Reliability as a Foundation</Heading>
          <Paragraph>
            Intelligence that operators cannot depend on consistently is not
            intelligence — it is a liability. We treat reliability as the
            non-negotiable foundation everything else is built on, not a future
            milestone.
          </Paragraph>
        </Card>
      </Grid>
    </Section>
    <Section bg="stripes" centered>
      <div slot="header" class="section--header">
        <div class="alt-title">Where We Are</div>
        <Heading level={2} size="2xl">Current Status</Heading>
        <Paragraph size="lg">
          Mermind is in early development. We are building a narrow, reliable
          foundation before expanding into broader capabilities. This means
          fewer features, more accuracy, and a deliberate sequence that does not
          skip foundational steps.
        </Paragraph>
      </div>
    </Section>
    <Section>
      <div slot="header" class="section--header">
        <div class="alt-title">Get Early Access</div>
        <Heading level={2} size="2xl">Be part of the journey</Heading>
        <Paragraph size="lg">
          Mermind is evolving step by step. Join the waitlist to stay informed
          and gain early access.
        </Paragraph>
      </div>
      <Card padding="lg" outlined>
        <Heading level={3} size="lg">Join the Waitlist</Heading>
        <Paragraph>
          Join the waitlist to follow along and be among the first to experience
          Mermind.
        </Paragraph>
        <WaitListForm />
      </Card>
    </Section>
  </main>
</Layout>
